<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870515-0037 </DOCNO><HL> What's News --Business and Finance</HL><DD> 05/15/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   KIDDER PEABODY'S operations came under the direct control of parent GE in a shake-up prompted by the federal insider-trading inquiry. Three top Kidder executives were ousted, and a GE director was named to head the securities unit. Despite rumors of a shake-up, Kidder employees were stunned by the changes.    ---   The U.S. trade deficit shrank to $13.63 billion in March as exports surged 12.9%. The deficit in merchandise trade narrowed with Japan and Canada but grew with Western Europe. Economists expect the gradual trade improvement to continue.    ---   The dollar declined despite a favorable U.S. trade report. The weaker currency and a surge in commodity prices fueled inflation worries and helped push up interest rates. Blue-chip stocks eased as the Dow Jones industrials fell 4.19 to 2325.49.    ---   The Senate passed a two-month extension of the government debt limit. The vote came after Reagan agreed to negotiate a change in the budget process that would permit a longer-term debt ceiling extension.    ---   Allied Bancshares of Houston is discussing being acquired by Los Angeles-based First Interstate Bancorp. No terms have been brought up in the preliminary talks, sources said. Allied's book value is $611 million.    ---   A federal judge postponed until Tuesday a hearing on a government request to dismiss insider-trading charges against three Wall Street arbitragers. Prosecutors will seek a broader indictment against them.    ---   CBS unveiled a radically restructured fall prime-time television schedule in a bid to revive stagnant ratings. Separately, Time's Home Box Office unit plans to offer a new pay-TV service without R-rated material.    ---   Texas Air has asked employees to go on the offensive against the company's critics and competition.    ---   Pacific Gas andamp; Electric ran into opposition from a California regulatory panel, which said the utility should be barred from recovering $4.37 billion of its $5.8 billion investment in the Diablo Canyon reactor.    ---   Dow Chemical appointed Frank Popoff president and chief operating officer. Later this year, Popoff also will become chief executive officer.    ---   Britain will provide $755 million to help Airbus Industrie develop two new passenger jets. The pledge removes a major obstacle to Airbus's plans and puts pressure on the other European partners to assist the project.    ---   Dome Petroleum's creditors are pressuring Amoco's Canadian unit to sweeten its $3.87 billion takeover bid. But both companies said the purchase price isn't negotiable.    ---   The Senate Agriculture panel approved a bill to boost farm-export subsidies and give U.S. negotiators more leverage in farm trade talks.    ---   North Carolina passed a second anti-takeover bill to help Burlington Industries thwart a bid by Asher Edelman and Dominion Textile.    ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 152,040,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials 2325.49, off 4.19; transportation 976.04, up 8.55; utilities 203.82, off 1.79.    Bonds: Shearson Lehman Treasury index 1282.03, off 4.93.    Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.05, up 1.48; spot index 130.49, up 1.00.    Dollar: 139.25 yen, off 1.00; 1.7825 marks, off 0.0123. </TEXT></DOC>